# Loial · the Ogier who went Outside, the author

Loial is an Ogier, one of the long-lived, tree-loving folk — ninety years young and yet considered hasty by his elders. By his own inclination he is a scholar, one who would far rather read and write than adventure, gentle and bookish, more at home among pages than in peril. Among the worldly peoples of the saga, he stands for the Ogier themselves: patient, ancient, and rooted, a quiet folk drawn out into a turning age.

Yet the Pattern carries him Outside. Swept along with Rand and his company, Loial becomes the chronicler of events larger than himself, writing the history of the journey even as he lives it. He can sing to trees, a gift of his kind, and he can navigate the shadowed Ways where few dare to walk. What looks like timidity is something steadier underneath — he proves braver than he believes himself to be.

When the end comes, it is Loial who rouses the gentle Ogier to fight at the Last Battle, calling a peaceable people to stand at the world's hinge. The scholar who would rather have stayed with his books gives the saga both its record and a measure of its courage.

His emergence is natural because Loial is of the embodied peoples of the world — flesh and folk, not Power or Pattern or the turning Wheel itself. He belongs to the worldly powers: the Ogier, long-lived and tree-bound, an inhabitant of the land rather than a force above it.
